image.altText: A police car outside National Zoo and Aquarium.

props.synopsis: Canberra man Jude Wijesinghe has been charged with murder over the apparent stabbing death of his coworker Tshewang Choden at the National Zoo and Aquarium in Canberra on Monday.

title.children: Canberra man charged with murder over apparent stabbing death of National Zoo and Aquarium coworker

props.synopsis: Lip-reading expert Tim Reedy gives evidence on CCTV of Bruce Lehrmann and Brittany Higgins speaking at a bar on the night of her alleged rape at Parliament House.

title.children: Brittany Higgins said 'I don't want to' when Bruce Lehrmann told her to finish drink, lip-reader tells Federal Court

image.altText: Two men exit the doors of a court building. The lawyer is wearing a suit, the other man is wearing shorts and a jumper.

props.synopsis: Former national rock-climbing coach Stephen Mitchell, who is already behind bars for persistent historical sexual abuse of six girls between 1994 and 2008, is found guilty of an act of indecency against a woman in Canberra in 2010.

title.children: Convicted child sex offender Stephen Mitchell found guilty of act of indecency against woman in 2010

image.altText: Bruce Lehrmann outside court.

props.synopsis: The former chief of staff in Senator Linda Reynolds's office tells the Federal Court she resisted pressure to go to the police after disclosures from Brittany Higgins about her alleged rape, saying she believed Ms Higgins should have control over the situation.

title.children: Former manager of Brittany Higgins and Bruce Lehrmann 'resisted' pressure to go to police over alleged incident

image.altText: Black hatchback that's been rear-ended and missing its boot.

props.synopsis: For much of the past four decades, Australia made steady progress on the road toll. But as the nation emerged from the COVID-19 pandemic, car crashes started to increase.

title.children: A significant increase in death rates on roads around the country has experts worried

image.altText: Woman in blue outfit cries as she talks to media

props.synopsis: Natasha Fyles has resigned as Northern Territory chief minister after failing to disclose her shareholdings in a mining company.

title.children: 'I don't have any excuse': NT Chief Minister Natasha Fyles resigns over shares

image.altText: Di Sanh Sunny Duong wearing a suit.

props.synopsis: A Melbourne businessman is facing up to 10 years in prison after using a hospital donation to secretly influence former federal minister Alan Tudge.

title.children: Chinese-Australian businessman guilty of attempting to influence then-minister Alan Tudge with hospital donation

image.altText: Rows of seized cocaine inside police plastic bags

props.synopsis: Five men have been charged after an alleged kidnapping attempt at a Sydney unit where police allegedly found $1 billion worth of cocaine in one of the biggest drug busts in the state's history.

title.children: Foiled kidnapping plot leads to discovery of $1 billion worth of cocaine in Sydney unit, police say

image.altText: a chinook helicopter on the runway

props.synopsis: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has announced applications for disaster recovery will open tomorrow, as Wujal Wujal residents evacuated.

title.children: Far North Queensland flood assistance payments announced, first Wujal Wujal evacuees land on higher ground

image.altText: A car on fire.

props.synopsis: The Pilliga bushfire has burnt through 112,000 hectares and, while storms are making firefighting efforts difficult, predicted rain is expected to help contain the main fire front.

title.children: Thunderstorms over NSW bushfire spark spot fires as firefighters wait for rain

image.altText: Smoke in the city with a view of the harbour, Harbour Bridge and residential terraces

props.synopsis: The smoke drifted from the Duck Creek, Pilliga Forest fire in regional NSW, which has burned more than 110,000 hectares of land.

title.children: Sydney blanketed by smoke from fire 400km away with thunderstorms predicted to follow

image.altText: A cartoon illustration of a light-skinned hand holding a small, white IUD and a dark-skinned hand holding a small, copper IUD.

props.synopsis: A public hospital in Melbourne has become one of the first in the country to offer women the green whistle when they get IUDs.

title.children: Hospital giving women a green whistle to help with IUD pain relief

image.altText: A woman sits smiling, holding a newborn baby.

props.synopsis: Christmas has arrived early for Kirsty Bryant, who has given birth to Henry — a healthy baby boy who grew within a uterus donated by her mother.

title.children: Australia's first uterus transplant recipient gives birth to healthy baby boy

image.altText: image of convicted terrorist Abdul Benbrika

props.synopsis: One of Australia's most notorious terrorists has been released on an extended supervision order for 12 months.

title.children: Convicted terrorist Abdul Nacer Benbrika walks free after nearly two decades behind bars

image.altText: Stretch of bitumen road with trees either side

props.synopsis: A senior detective tells an inquest into the historic deaths of two Aboriginal girls on a NSW highway that manslaughter charges against a non-Indigenous man would have been more appropriate.

title.children: Senior detective slams initial NSW Police investigation into 1987 deaths of Aboriginal cousins near Bourke

image.altText: A child on a watermelon floatie.

props.synopsis: Western Sydney's first beach opens to the public, with "crystal-clear" water and few geese droppings.

title.children: Man-made Western Sydney beach dubbed 'Pondi' passes the swim test

image.altText: Ozempic is displayed in a pharmacy in Provo

props.synopsis: Not since Viagra has the world of medicine seen a bigger "accident" but if Ozempic can tackle the challenges obesity has presented in recent decades, there could be a profound impact on the global economy, writes Ian Verrender.

title.children: The accidental arrival of Ozempic could affect the health of the global economy

image.altText: A plane with Turkish Airlines branding flies over a dense cityscape.

props.synopsis: Experts say more air travel destinations are expected to open up at a lower cost following a government decision to grant Turkish Airlines an additional 35 weekly flights in and out of Australia by 2025.

title.children: Cheaper international flights on the horizon after government approves Turkish Airlines bid

image.altText: Close up of Catherine King

props.synopsis: The transport minister says Türkiye was approved for a major expansion in flight capacity because it would open a new market for Australia, acknowledging the sector was still recovering from the COVID-19 pandemic.

title.children: Catherine King says Turkish Airlines expansion 'routine' decision that will open new market

image.altText: Smoke billows from a grass fire.

props.synopsis: A cattle industry survey shows millions of dollars in losses from deliberately lit fires, with pastoralists calling for more concrete action.

title.children: Calls to send arson squad to WA's north after 2 million hectares burnt in deliberately lit bushfires

image.altText: A man pushes a wheelie bin through a butcher shop.

props.synopsis: Legs of ham worth $200 each were stuffed into a wheelie bin in a bizarre Sunshine Coast robbery that threatened to ruin Christmas lunch for dozens of families.

title.children: How a Grinch failed to steal Christmas from family-run butcher shop

image.altText: volcano (4)

props.synopsis: The Reykjanes peninsula in recent years saw several eruptions in unpopulated areas, but the latest outbreak could pose a risk to the Grindavik town.

title.children: Icelandic volcano erupts following weeks of intense earthquakes

image.altText: Four Israeli tanks drive in a line, with small Israeli flags flying from them.

props.synopsis: Israel's objectives of recovering all its hostages and destroying Hamas are only part of the story of why this war may be a long one, writes Mick Ryan.

title.children: Israel and Hamas are locked in a deathmatch that may continue for some time — at heavy cost

image.altText: a man wearing glasses standing in front of the press with another man standing next to him

props.synopsis: Former Labor foreign ministers Bob Carr and Gareth Evans are among 203 current and former politicians who have signed a letter calling for a ceasefire in Gaza and pledging support for Palestinians.

title.children: Current and former MPs from across political spectrum sign letter calling for review of relationship with Israel

image.altText: A close shot of Health Minister Mark Butler's face, looking serious.

props.synopsis: Under federal law, health insurers can increase premiums once a year but must seek the minister's approval.

title.children: Health minister tells insurers to 'have another go' after rejecting premium increases

image.altText: Three men in white shirts sit in a line

props.synopsis: One of the three men in the video says the elderly hostages who have health issues are suffering "in very harsh conditions," as Israel denounces it as a "criminal, terrorist video".

title.children: Hamas releases video of three hostages who say they are 'suffering greatly'

image.altText: An out of focus man and woman walk past a building with glass sliding doors and a sign reading Reserve Bank of Australia.

props.synopsis: Newly released minutes from the RBA's December cash rate meeting show the central bank decided to leave official interest rates on hold after seeing "encouraging signs" that aggressive hikes were working to win the inflation battle.

title.children: Reserve Bank left rates on hold after 'encouraging signs' that aggressive hikes were taming inflation

image.altText: This wide image also shows 14 of the planet’s 27 moons

props.synopsis: NASA shares new images of the blue-green planet to celebrate the space telescope turning two on December 25.

title.children: NASA releases new images of Uranus's rings captured with the James Webb Space Telescope

image.altText: Alyssa Healy sits in the old members stand at the SCG with her captain's blazer and baggy green on

props.synopsis: The only woman to have ever captained, kept wicket and opened the batting in a Test, has backed new leader Alyssa Healy to continue in the same prominent roles.

title.children: 'You were always in the game': Marg Jennings backs Alyssa Healy to captain, keep and open

image.altText: Rinky Hijikata adjusts his cap during a US Open match against Frances Tiafoe.

props.synopsis: Rinky Hijikata knows one swallow doesn't make a summer as the emerging star stays firmly grounded after a breakout year on the ATP Tour.

title.children: Rinky Hijikata ready to earn his stripes all over again after breakout 2023

image.altText: AFLW

props.synopsis: On a big night for the AFLW's rising stars, Geelong select a father-daughter pick whose dad played with Sam Newman and Doug Wade in the 60s.

title.children: Five quick hits — the 50-year gap between dad and daughter at Geelong and the Demons steal a multi-sport champion
